Cauvery water dispute: State-wide bandh brings Karnataka to a halt.

A dawn-to-dusk Karnataka bandh called by pro-Kannada outfits protest against the Supreme Court's direction to release Cauvery river water to Tamil Nadu throws normal life out of gear.

Over 1100 organisations including 800 unions are said ti be supporting bandh call. State KSRTC, BMTC buses to stay off roads, auto rickshaws and taxis including Ola and uber to not ply. Banks, Government offices and schools including private to be closed. Malls, theaters, petrol bunks and restaurants to be closed.

Winner of the category The Grassroots Soldiers is Laxman Singh and here is his story: 

#MyAmazingIndians – The Water Warrior of Laporiya

Laxman Singh developed the Chauka system to help villagers of Laporiya save their harvests from the extreme weather conditions. This unique water harvesting technique uses shallow pits where rain water helps recharge the groundwater.

Laxman Singh is the founder of the Gram Vikas Navyuvak Mandal of Laporiya. This grassroot soldier's continuous efforts over time have converted a parched region into lush arable land.

Winner of the category Educators of India is Dharampal Saini and here is his story

#MyAmazingIndians – Tau of Bastar increased literacy from 1% to 65%

Dharampal Saini, a disciple of Vinoba Bhave, always wanted to better the state of education for girls in the hinterland of Chhattisgarh. He challenged all tribal traditions and beliefs of the naxal belt of Bastar and founded 'Mata Rukmani Seva Sansthan' in 1976. 

Over the last 4 decades, Dharampal Saini's efforts have resulted in the growth of the literacy rate from 1% in 1976 to over 65% at present. Being an athletic champion himself, he believes in the 'play and learn' style of education. Over the years, this practice has produced several national level players.

Winner of the category Ordinary Indians, Extraordinary Achievements is Manimaran and here is his story:

#MyAmazingIndians – Leprosy patients get a new lease of life

Manimaran has given the leprosy struck patients of Tiruvannamalai a new lease of life. This messiah of hope earns only to contribute to their lives. His hard work and dedication has helped him establish World People Service Center, where he not only cleans their wounds but also heals their hearts. His extraordinary initiative was not only praised but also encouraged by former President of India, APJ Abdul Kalam. 

Manimaran believes, "Everybody is born with compassion within them. Service is a feeling that comes from within and can definitely be achieved". His belief and devotion has helped him cure over 360 leprosy patients.

#MyAmazingIndians – Kisan Call Centre

Amit Sinha is the founder of Unnati, an agriculture-based services company that provides support and inputs to thousands of farmers. His initiative aims to bring economic prosperity and well-being to farmers. 

Unnati provides knowledge and information relevant to a farmer's specific farming needs, market linkages for his output, best inputs at the best price and financial support. Another unique feature of this initiative is the Kisan Call Centre. This means that scientific advice on crop cultivation is just a call away for the farmers. Unnati is doing its best to support farmers for profitable and sustainable farming.

#MyAmazingIndians – Swiss couple helping children in Tamil Nadu

Udo and Wilma Gastel came to India from Switzerland in 2005 and they were moved to see the plight of families affected by the tsunami.
